const DR=[{id:1,n:"GLP-1 Demand Destruction",ct:16,cl:C.red,ic:"💊",ds:"Pharmacological appetite suppression at population scale. 16% US household penetration rising. Savory -10%, sweets -9%. Not a diet — a neurological intervention. By 2036: oral generics at $28/month, 40%+ have tried, 26% sustained use. 'Managed appetite' becomes background infrastructure."},{id:2,n:"Regulatory Encirclement",ct:19,cl:C.purple,ic:"⚖️",ds:"Tax + label + ad ban + placement + reporting + school exclusion + procurement. 116 countries taxing sugar. UK HFSS ad ban live. Chile model spreading. WHO '3 by 35'. By 2036: no unregulated confectionery market above $1B remains."},{id:3,n:"UPF Reclassification",ct:16,cl:C.amber,ic:"🧪",ds:"FDA defining UPF. State school bans. Municipal lawsuits. AG coordination. Lancet consensus. By 2036: tobacco trajectory completes — litigation, settlement, mandatory reformulation timelines, public nuisance designation."},{id:4,n:"Cocoa Supply Crisis",ct:16,cl:"#8B4513",ic:"🍫",ds:"Record volatility. Structural underinvestment. Climate disease. JPM: $6,000+/t new floor. By 2036: precision fermentation produces cocoa compounds at fraction of agricultural cost. Chocolate bifurcates: luxury vs cocoa-free mass market."},{id:5,n:"Generational Taste Shift",ct:16,cl:C.blue,ic:"🧬",ds:"Protein-first. Functional. Permissible indulgence. TikTok cycles. By 2036: Gen Alpha enters prime snacking age having never formed habitual confectionery consumption. The protein orthodoxy. 'What does this DO for me?'"},{id:6,n:"Retail Format Disruption",ct:12,cl:C.social,ic:"🏪",ds:"Q-commerce, checkout-free, hybrid work, AI shopping agents, HFSS placement. By 2036: 31%+ US grocery AI-mediated. The physical temptation moment designed out. Confectionery algorithmically erased."},{id:7,n:"Kellanova Portfolio Convergence",ct:22,cl:C.green,ic:"🔗",ds:"$36B closed Dec 2025. Pringles, Cheez-It, Pop-Tarts, RXBAR, and Kellogg's international cereal portfolio. Cereal is the acquisition's most complex asset: 25-year US volume decline, explicitly HFSS Category 3, visibly ultra-processed — but reformulatable below thresholds, and still growing in EU/Asia/Middle East. By 2036: savoury + functional + international cereal generate more operating profit than confectionery. 'Core' becomes 'legacy.'"},{id:8,n:"Sugar Alternative Cost Curve",ct:8,cl:C.goldBright,ic:"🧂",ds:"Allulose, stevia, monk fruit. AI reformulation. By 2036: allulose at sugar parity. 80% portfolio navigable below HFSS. But 'reformulated' reads as 'admission of guilt.'"},{id:9,n:"Emerging Market Growth Divergence",ct:10,cl:C.technology,ic:"🌍",ds:"India +8-10%. Africa youngest. But every growth market simultaneously becoming regulated. By 2036: no unregulated confectionery markets above $1B."},{id:10,n:"Breakfast Occasion Collapse",ct:8,cl:"#FF8C42",ic:"🥣",ds:"Cold cereal volumes declining 25+ consecutive years. US down 13% in 4 years (2.5B→2.1B boxes). Breakfast itself fragmenting: Gen Z skipping or grabbing portable formats. Cereal explicitly HFSS Category 3 in UK. UPF-classified everywhere. Protein insurgents (Magic Spoon) reframing the category. Toaster pastries cannibalising from within. By 2036: cereal survives only where it reformulates below thresholds and repositions beyond breakfast — or in international growth markets where penetration is still expanding."}];

const SC=[{id:1,ti:"Probable",dv:[1,5],tt:"The Pharmacological Reset",tl:"When 40% of your core consumer base has been neurologically rewired to not want what you sell, the question isn't share — it's category survival.",dp:`March 2036. The building on West Randolph in Chicago that houses Mars Snacking — the same one that was Kellanova's headquarters — has a gym on the second floor. At 7am the gym is full. The vending machines on every floor have been restocked three times in eighteen months. The first restock, 2034, added RXBAR, KIND, Pringles Protein. The second, 2035, removed Snickers and Twix from floors 3-8, replaced them with single-serve "micro-meal pods" from a Singapore startup. The third restock last month replaced the vending machines entirely with smart fridges stocked by a local meal-prep company.

Mars Snacking's own employees don't eat Mars Snacking products.

Generic oral semaglutide has been available since 2031 at $28/month. Adoption crossed 40% of US adults who have tried it; sustained use sits at 26%. The combination with AI nutritional coaching — apps that track eating, adjust macros, integrate with pharmacy — has created "managed appetite." Not a diet, not a choice, but a baseline physiological state for roughly a quarter of Americans.

The craving signal that sent someone to a vending machine at 3pm doesn't fire. GLP-1 receptor agonists reduce activity in the brain's reward centres. People on these drugs don't resist chocolate. They don't think about it. The phenomenological experience, described across thousands of patient interviews, is not willpower. It is absence.

Confectionery revenue has declined 34% in real terms since 2025 in US. Not because products taste worse or cost more. Because the neurological infrastructure of craving that supported impulse confectionery has been pharmaceutically dismantled. Pringles is down 8%. RXBAR up 41%. KIND up 19%. Kellanova savoury brands flat in volume, +12% in value.

A food scientist named Priya Deshmukh stares at her "appetite erosion" dashboard. Confectionery occasions per capita down 31% since 2025. The break room on the eighth floor still has a bowl of M&M's by the coffee machine. Nobody has taken one since Tuesday. It is now Friday.`,ss:"Small confectionery makers eliminated. Convenience workers lose hours. Cocoa farmer demand collapses. Cultural ritual of shared sweets erodes.",ka:"GLP-1 side effects or safety concerns cap sustained adoption below 15%.",dm:{d:90,a:15,r:95,v:85}},{id:2,ti:"Probable",dv:[2,3],tt:"The Regulatory Endgame",tl:"The last unregulated confectionery market above $1 billion closed in 2034. Mars operates where every product carries a warning, every ad requires a lawyer, and every shelf placement is a negotiation.",dp:`November 2036. In Mars's London office, Suki Patel reviews a compliance matrix. 47 rows (markets), 12 columns: Sugar Tax, FOP Label, Ad Watershed, Online Ads, Placement, Schools, Procurement, UPF Class, Sales Reporting, Age Check, Promos, Litigation. Three green cells in the entire matrix — all "Age Verification," for markets that haven't introduced it yet.

The UK was the template. HFSS ad ban (Jan 2026) → promotional restrictions (2027) → mandatory sales reporting (2028) → confectionery sugar levy (2030). EU harmonised by 2032: black octagon labels, 9pm watershed, total online ban, mandatory UPF classification. India followed 2033. The US slower but more punishing: state UPF school bans spreading to 20+ states, FDA's formal UPF definition (2029), and state AG litigation wave (2028-2034) producing de facto national regulation.

Mars's creative team — based at adam&eveTBWA — has become expert in "negative space advertising." The 2035 Snickers Christmas campaign: a man in a post office queue, looking tired. He unwraps something from his pocket. You never see what it is. Never see a product. Endline: "You're not you when you're hungry." It won a Cannes Grand Prix. The strategy director called it "the most expensive brand film ever made about something you can't show."

Compliance cost across 47 regulated markets: 4.2% of revenue. For Snickers, this exceeds the marketing budget. For the Kellogg's cereal portfolio, the maths are different but the direction is the same: breakfast cereals are Category 3 in every HFSS framework, and the reformulated range competes against protein cereals and overnight oats that never needed reformulation.

In a corridor, a junior strategist named Tom Chen shows a deck proving the latest Twix brand campaign increased consideration 14%. The problem: consideration doesn't convert when the product has a black octagon, can't sit at checkout, costs 22% more from the sugar levy, and was described on the BBC last night as "ultra-processed."`,ss:"Advertising industry contracts. Creative agencies lose accounts. Small food brands can't afford compliance. Innovation freezes as R&D shifts to compliance.",ka:"Regulatory fragmentation prevents implementation. Markets compete on lax regulation.",dm:{d:80,a:10,r:95,v:75}},{id:3,ti:"Probable",dv:[4,8],tt:"The Cocoa Schism",tl:"In 2036, 'chocolate' means two different things depending on your income. One costs $12. The other doesn't contain cocoa.",dp:`February 2036. In a Zurich patisserie — marble counter, bonbons behind glass — a card reads: "Single-origin Ecuadorian Cacao Nacional. EUDR-verified." Box of twelve: 96 CHF.

Seven thousand kilometres south, the International Cocoa Organization's 2036 report confirms structural relocation. Ecuador produces more than Ghana. Brazil's Bahia at capacity. West Africa's share: from 70% to 54%, still falling.

In a Memphis Walmart, a consumer picks up a "chocolate-style" bar — the legal term since the EU's 2033 ruling that <20% cocoa can't say "chocolate." The coating is Cargill's NextCoa 3.0: precision-fermented flavour molecules, roasted oat, shea butter. $1.49. Consumer testing: 71% can't distinguish it from the Twix it replaced.

Mars's "Portfolio Cocoa Dependency Ratio" — introduced 2026 — reads 29%, down from 68% in 2024. Three sources: Kellanova savoury (zero cocoa), six major SKUs reformulated to alternatives, three chocolate variants discontinued.

In a testing kitchen, food scientist Aisha Bello runs blind panels. Seven of twelve prefer original. Three can't tell. Two prefer new. Seven out of twelve for original is actually their best result in two years.

Mars's cocoa procurement bill: -41% in real terms despite $7,400/t — because they buy 53% less. The CFO's slide: "Portfolio Cocoa Dependency Ratio." The board meeting: "Are we still a chocolate company?" The honest answer: no.`,ss:"West African farmers face double demand destruction. Two million families lose income. Cultural meaning of chocolate as democratic pleasure erodes. Class determines who eats 'real' chocolate.",ka:"Precision fermentation fails at scale. Consumer rejection, novel food regulation, or costs never reach parity.",dm:{d:70,a:40,r:90,v:65}},{id:4,ti:"Probable",dv:[6,1],tt:"The Algorithmic Shelf",tl:"31% of US grocery purchases made by AI agents. They don't impulse-buy. They don't see displays. They don't crave chocolate at 3pm.",dp:`September 2036. David Chen, 33, San Francisco. Hasn't been inside a grocery store in fourteen months. His fridge has a camera. Pantry has weight sensors. An AI agent monitors both, cross-references his meal plan (optimised for his GLP-1 protocol and running schedule), places Instacart orders to a locker in his building.

David doesn't buy confectionery. Not by decision. Because his AI agent never adds it. The agent optimises: high protein, low added sugar, <$85/week, fresh. Confectionery passes none of these filters. It has never appeared in a recommendation. Zero probability of surfacing.

Meera Kapoor, Mars head of digital commerce, has been articulating this since 2033. Her deck, "The Invisible Category": confectionery faces algorithmic erasure. In a world where software optimises for stated preferences, products that exist as impulse purchases — relying on being seen at the right moment — have no mechanism of entry.

Pringles has a mechanism. David's agent adds a tube for Saturday gaming sessions — social, scheduled, explicit. Confectionery's occasion — the unplanned craving, the 3pm vending machine — is precisely the unstructured desire algorithmic purchasing eliminates.

31% of US grocery is AI-mediated. Under 35: 44%. In none of these systems does confectionery have a natural home.

The data team runs a simulation. If they could get confectionery into 5% of AI agent recommendation lists, it would be worth $340M in incremental US revenue. The agents' recommendation APIs are technically open. But the optimisation criteria — protein, fiber, added sugar, cost per nutrient — systematically exclude every confectionery product in the portfolio. You can't buy your way onto an algorithm that defines you as nutritionally irrelevant.`,ss:"Food discovery narrows. Serendipitous taste vanishes. Small artisans lose route to market. Pleasure of choosing outsourced.",ka:"Consumers reject AI-mediated purchasing. Tactile grocery experience reasserts.",dm:{d:50,a:25,r:85,v:70}},{id:5,ti:"Probable",dv:[7,9],tt:"The $36 Billion Question, Answered",tl:"By 2036, Kellanova savoury brands generate more operating profit than Mars's entire confectionery portfolio. The acquisition wasn't diversification. It was succession planning.",dp:`June 2036. McLean, Virginia. Annual Mars board review. Internal documents: snacking division $31.4B, roughly flat since 2026. But composition transformed.

2024 (pre-Kellanova): confectionery = 62% revenue, 58% operating profit.
2036: confectionery = 38% revenue, 29% operating profit.
Savoury + functional = 44% revenue, 52% operating profit.

The surprise in the numbers is the cereal portfolio. When Mars acquired Kellanova, the US cereal business had already been separated (sold to Ferrero via WK Kellogg). What Mars kept was the international cereal operation — Kellogg's branded cereals across Europe, Asia, and the Middle East. In 2026, this looked like a legacy asset: declining Western volumes, HFSS-classified in the UK, clearly ultra-processed by any definition. The internal consensus was that international cereal would be a drag.

It wasn't. The reformulation team applied the same allulose-stevia methodology to the cereal portfolio that they'd used on confectionery, and it worked faster. Cereal formulations are simpler than chocolate — fewer ingredients, more tolerance for sugar substitution. By 2030, 70% of the Kellogg's cereal range in HFSS-regulated markets scored below threshold. They could be advertised, placed at checkout, sold in schools. In India, where cereal penetration was still in single digits, the reformulated range launched with protein-fortified variants that positioned against traditional breakfast, not against other cereals. In the Gulf states, Kellogg's became the first major cereal brand with a clean HFSS score, capturing shelf space competitors lost.

The US cereal market — someone else's problem since the Kellanova/WK Kellogg split — continued its 25-year decline. But Mars didn't own that decline. It owned the international growth story.

Gurugram, outside Delhi. Mars India's fastest-growing market — not for confectionery. Pringles India launched Tandoori Masala, Gunpowder Spice: +340% in four years. RXBAR #2 protein bar on Indian q-commerce. Pop-Tarts adapted with cardamom, saffron. M&M's and Snickers stable but not growing — FSSAI's red triangles since 2033 made urban consumers hesitant.

Lagos. Pringles launched 2029, immediately captured social-snacking. Mars's confectionery never established a foothold. Pringles did.

A second-generation board member asks: "At what point do we acknowledge we're no longer a confectionery company with a savoury division, but a savoury company with a confectionery legacy?"

Nobody answers immediately. The Pet Care CEO — Mars's other major division — breaks the silence: "We answered that question with Pet Care twenty years ago. We just didn't call it that."

The Kellanova acquisition thesis holds. But the thesis has evolved. In 2024, the narrative was diversification. In 2036, the honest description is succession. Pringles didn't hedge the confectionery core. It replaced it.`,ss:"Mars's century-old confectionery identity dissolves. Heritage brands become second-tier. Long-tenured marketers redirected. What does 'Mars' mean without chocolate?",ka:"Savoury faces its own reckoning: salt taxes, UPF classification of Pringles/Cheez-It, or generational turn against crisps.",dm:{d:75,a:60,r:90,v:80}},{id:6,ti:"Deep",dv:[3,2],tt:"The Controlled Category",tl:"A federal judge ruled M&M's qualified as a 'product designed to maximise compulsive consumption.' Mars settled for $2.1 billion.",dp:`April 2036. Case No. 3:31-cv-00847, Southern District of Mississippi. 847 pages. Modelled on the 1998 Master Tobacco Settlement Agreement.

Key finding: manufacturers "designed, marketed, and distributed products engineered to maximise palatability and consumption frequency in a manner that they knew, or should have known, contributed to population-level metabolic disease."

Litigation began 2028 — twelve state AGs, emboldened by Kennedy's 2025 call. Mars wasn't the primary target. Third to settle, after settlements in 2032-33.

Terms: $2.1B to nutrition fund. Mandatory UPF disclosure on all packaging. Elimination of all marketing to under-18 — not restricted, eliminated. 60% of portfolio to meet reformulated UPF standards by 2038. And: annual independent audit assessing "compulsive consumption design."

"Compulsive consumption design" — sugar/fat/salt ratios + texture engineering + flavour layering activating reward pathways analogously to addictive substances. Snickers — caramel-nougat-chocolate-peanut layering — cited specifically in the Mississippi filing.

The bar hasn't been reformulated. Its packaging now carries a black-bordered panel: "This product classified as ultra-processed under the Federal UPF Standard (2029). Contains ingredients associated with compulsive consumption patterns."

Snickers sales: -58% since 2025.

In the lobby of Mars's McLean headquarters, a framed advertisement from 1930 shows a woman biting into a Milky Way bar with unguarded pleasure. Next to it, a 2036 compliance poster lists the fourteen disclosures now legally required on confectionery packaging in the United States.`,ss:"Innovation freezes. Mid-size companies can't absorb settlement. Mass consolidation. Pleasure of eating pathologised.",ka:"Courts reject causation. Specific formulations don't directly cause metabolic disease — evidentiary grounds.",dm:{d:40,a:5,r:95,v:40}},{id:7,ti:"Deep",dv:[8,2],tt:"The Allulose Arbitrage",tl:"Mars reformulated everything. Scored below every threshold. Reopened every channel. Then discovered consumers don't trust the word 'reformulated.'",dp:`October 2035. "Project Goldilocks: Final Status Report." 41 of top 50 SKUs reformulated with allulose-sugar blends and next-gen stevia. All 41 score below UK NPM threshold. All 41 outside HFSS. All 41 can be advertised pre-watershed, placed at checkout, sold in school tuck shops.

Allulose reached sugar price parity in 2033. Chinese production: $0.42/kg vs refined sugar $0.44/kg. Taste gap closed by AI: 14,000 combinations tested across top SKUs, 2028-2033.

Consumer tracking: 62% of regular Snickers buyers aware of reformulation. Of those: 34% positive, 41% neutral, 25% negative — "not the real thing." The negative segment grew from 8% (2031) to 25% today. Correlates: over 45, lower income, US South, Northern England, rural Germany.

The problem isn't the reformulation. It's the signal. In a world where UPF is cultural, where ultra-processing = corporate deception, where "they changed the recipe" = "they got caught" — reformulation reads as admission of guilt.

The CFO calls it "the HFSS arbitrage." It works financially: pre-watershed TV access generates 23% more media value. But consumer trust data shows a growing segment that has mentally reclassified the products from "treat" to "reformulated product" — and "reformulated product" doesn't trigger the same reward response as "treat."

The irony: the technical achievement is extraordinary. The commercial outcome is a brand that can now be advertised everywhere but is wanted slightly less everywhere.`,ss:"Natural sugar producers lose share. Clean-label advocates treat allulose as 'another UPF ingredient.' Trust gap widens.",ka:"Allulose costs stall. Or regulators reclassify as novel food.",dm:{d:55,a:50,r:80,v:50}},{id:8,ti:"Deep",dv:[5,1],tt:"The Protein Orthodoxy",tl:"'How much protein?' is the first question about every snack. Confectionery is the one category that can never answer it.",dp:`January 2036. Whole Foods, Austin, Texas. Snack aisle reorganised — not by type but by grams of protein per serving.

15g+ at eye level: RXBAR, Quest, Barebells, Built, and FORGED — a new Mars brand (2034) with pea-whey core in dark chocolate shell. 8-15g below: KIND Protein, Clif, nut butters. 3-8g: trail mixes, Cheez-It Protein (2032). Bottom shelf, near floor: traditional confectionery. Snickers. M&M's. Skittles. Less than 3g.

Jordan Park, 19, picks up M&M's. Sees "2g protein per serving." Puts it back. Takes a FORGED bar. Asked why: "I mean, it's only 2 grams." As though explaining something obvious to a child.

The "protein orthodoxy": not a diet trend, not bodybuilding culture. A heuristic. More protein = better. Less = not worth it. Origin: GLP-1 protein prioritisation (prevent muscle loss) + social media fitness + functional eating convergence.

Confectionery's problem is structural. Chocolate, sugar, caramel, nougat are not high-protein. You can add protein but the result is a protein bar with chocolate flavouring. Mars already makes that — RXBAR.

Mars consumer insight: 73% of 18-25 US consumers check protein content before any snack purchase. 89% consider <5g "not worth it." The company's confectionery R&D team spent $14M developing a "high-protein Snickers" in 2033. Consumer testing was catastrophic: "It doesn't taste like Snickers anymore" (67%) and "If I wanted protein I'd eat an RXBAR" (54%). The project was shelved.

The question nobody at Mars wants to ask: if confectionery can never win the protein heuristic, and the protein heuristic is now the default consumer filter, is confectionery structurally obsolete as a mainstream snacking format?`,ss:"Nutrient reductionism impoverishes food culture. Pleasure for taste alone culturally suspect. Carbohydrate traditions decline. Disordered eating from 'protein anxiety.'",ka:"Protein obsession is cyclical. 'Protein fatigue' or new paradigm rebalances priorities.",dm:{d:65,a:30,r:85,v:75}},{id:9,ti:"Cassandra",dv:[5,3],tt:"The Cultural Extinction",tl:"Confectionery doesn't die from regulation, pharmacology, or economics. It dies from meaning. Gen Alpha doesn't reject chocolate. They simply don't recognise it.",dp:`December 2036. Dr. Keiko Tanaka publishes "The Last Sweet Tooth" in the Journal of Consumer Culture. Four years of ethnographic fieldwork, six countries, 2,400 consumers aged 14-24.

Central finding: for people born after 2008, confectionery carries no cultural meaning. Not forbidden, not expensive, not unhealthy in their framing. Simply absent from their identity.

Seoul, 21-year-old, shown a Snickers: "That's something my dad eats. Like, at a petrol station." London, 17: "Christmas? My nan gave me some." São Paulo, 23: "Checkout stuff. I don't look at those things." Lagos, 19, asked Pringles vs M&M's: "Pringles is for football with people. M&M's — maybe a kid's party?"

Confectionery is generationally coded. It belongs to an older paradigm. The rejection isn't dietary or economic. It's semiotic. Confectionery has lost its signs. It no longer means pleasure, rebellion, comfort, or reward to this generation. It means their parents' world.

Tanaka draws the parallel to tobacco. Smoking didn't decline primarily from regulation. It declined when it ceased to be culturally aspirational. When it became associated with an older generation rather than youth rebellion, the category entered terminal decline. Not overnight — over decades. But irreversibly.

The irony: Pringles thrives. Same demographic. Not healthier. Social, shareable, remixable, no generational baggage. Pop-Tarts survived through ironic cultural positioning. RXBAR through function. Confectionery's crisis is not contents. It's meaning.

On page 247, Tanaka reproduces a photograph from Mars's Chicago innovation lab. A whiteboard, dated 2029, red marker: "What if they simply don't want what we make?" Written as provocation. By 2036 it reads as epitaph.`,ss:"Family confectioners fade. Craft traditions lost. Cultural ritual of sweets as celebration, comfort, love erodes. Something irreplaceable gone.",ka:"Nostalgia is renewable. Creative investment makes chocolate culturally aspirational again.",dm:{d:20,a:10,r:95,v:25}}];

